      <div class='hentry member_contribution'>
        <a name='S6CV0364P0_20010314_WH_83'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-christopher-fraser' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S6CV0364P0_20010314_WH_83' title='Link to this speech by Mr Christopher Fraser' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-christopher-fraser" title="Mr Christopher Fraser">Mr. Fraser</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            Now I will have my say. I am sure that the hon. Member for Hove can speak later if time permits.</p><p>
            We do not know the cost of Wembley stadium or what progress has been made, yet it is set to begin hosting sporting events in 2004. We do not know how much the proposed Lee Valley stadium will cost or when progress will be made towards its development, yet we are assured that it will be ready to host the 2005 world athletics championships. In addition, we do not know whether those plans will aid or hinder a future Olympic bid for London. We do know that the Department and the Government have presided over yet another fiasco. We thought that things could only get better after the dome, but sadly they have not.</p><p>
            Ken Bates, who was at the time chairman of Wembley National Stadium Ltd., accused the Minister of "interfering" in the redevelopment of Wembley football
            
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_267wh' title='Col. 267WH &mdash; HC Deb 14 March 2001 vol 364 c267WH' name='column_267wh' href='#column_267wh' rel='bookmark'>267WH</a>
            stadium and of "constantly undermining" him. He also said that her period of office had been characterised by ignorance. I have an awful lot of respect for her in many other spheres, but I should like her to respond to that point made against her by Ken Bates. Appearing before the Culture, Media and Sport Committee, on which I serve, he said that it was
            <q>more in sorrow than in anger</q>
            that he contrasted the "mess over Wembley" with the success of the Australian Olympic stadium. He said that there had been
